  <content>
    <para id="para-00001">The addition of a nucleophile to a polar C=O bond is the key step in three of the four major carbonyl-group reactions. We saw in the chapter on <link document="m00211">Aldehydes and Ketones: Nucleophilic Addition Reactions</link> that when a nucleophile adds to an aldehyde or ketone, the initially formed tetrahedral intermediate can be protonated to yield an alcohol. When a nucleophile adds to a carboxylic acid derivative, however, a different reaction path is taken. The initially formed tetrahedral intermediate eliminates one of the two substituents originally bonded to the carbonyl carbon, leading to a net <term id="term-00001">nucleophilic acyl substitution reaction</term> (<link target-id="fig-00001"/>).</para>
    <figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two reactions. The first reaction is labeled ‘(a) Aldehyde or ketone: nucleophilic addition.’ A carbonyl compound reacts with blue Nu anion that shows two electrons to yield an Alkoxide ion intermediate that reacts with hydronium ion (highlighted in pink) to yield an alcohol. The carbonyl compound shows a central carbonyl group bonded to an R and R’. An arrow from the electrons of Nu points to the carbon. An arrow from the carbonyl bond points to oxygen that shows four electrons. The Alkoxide ion intermediate shows a carbon dash bonded to R wedge bonded to R’ and single bonded to blue Nu and oxygen anion that shows six electrons. The alcohol shows a carbon dash bonded to R wedge bonded to R’ and single bonded to Nu and pink hydroxyl group. The oxygen atoms are highlighted in pink. The second reaction is labeled ‘(b) Carboxylic acid derivative: nucleophilic acyl substitution.’ A carbonyl compound reacts with blue Nu anion that shows two electrons to yield an Alkoxide ion intermediate that reacts to yield a new carbonyl compound and Y anion. The carbonyl compound shows a central carbonyl group bonded to an R and green Y. An arrow from the electrons of blue Nu points to the carbon. An arrow from the carbonyl bond points to oxygen that shows four electrons. The Alkoxide ion intermediate shows a carbon dash bonded to R wedge bonded to green Y and single bonded to Nu and oxygen anion that shows six electrons. The new carbonyl compound shows a carbonyl group bonded to R and Nu. The oxygen atoms are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_02_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption><emphasis effect="bold">The general mechanisms of nucleophilic addition and nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions.</emphasis> Both reactions begin with addition of a nucleophile to a polar C=O bond to give a tetrahedral, alkoxide ion intermediate. <emphasis effect="bold">(a)</emphasis> The intermediate formed from an aldehyde or ketone is protonated to give an alcohol, but <emphasis effect="bold">(b)</emphasis> the intermediate formed from a carboxylic acid derivative expels a leaving group to give a new carbonyl compound.</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00002">The difference in behavior between aldehydes/ketones and carboxylic acid derivatives is a consequence of structure. Carboxylic acid derivatives have an acyl carbon bonded to a group  – Y that can act as a leaving group, often as a stable anion. As soon as the tetrahedral intermediate is formed, the leaving group is expelled to generate a new carbonyl compound. Aldehydes and ketones, however, have no such leaving group, however, and therefore don’t undergo substitution.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="An illustration shows the structures of three compounds. The first structure a carboxylic acid derivative shows a carbonyl group bonded to R and green Y (a leaving group). The second and third structures are inside parentheses. The second structure an aldehyde shows a carbonyl group bonded to R and blue hydrogen (not a leaving group). The third structure a ketone shows a carbonyl group bonded to R and blue R’ (not a leaving group). The oxygen atoms are highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_02_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00003">The net effect of the addition/elimination sequence is a substitution of the nucleophile for the  – Y group that was originally bonded to the acyl carbon. Thus, the overall reaction is superficially similar to the kind of nucleophilic substitution that occurs during an S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction <emphasis effect="bold">(<link document="m00124">Section 11.3</link>)</emphasis>, but the mechanisms of the two reactions are completely different. An S<sub>N</sub>2 reaction occurs in a single step by backside displacement of the leaving group, while a nucleophilic acyl substitution takes place in two steps and involves a tetrahedral intermediate.</para>
