    </figure>
    <example id="exam-00001">
    <title>Predicting the Product of a Nucleophilic Acyl Substitution Reaction</title>
    <para id="para-00011">Predict the product of the following nucleophilic acyl substitution reaction of benzoyl chloride with 2-propanol:</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00007">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction of Benzoyl chloride in the presence of 2-propanol to yield an unknown product. Benzoyl chloride shows benzene bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to chlorine. 2-propanol shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group bonded to a methyl group. The methine group is bonded to a hydroxyl group at the top.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_02_008.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00012"><title><span class="red-text">Strategy</span></title> A nucleophilic acyl substitution reaction involves the substitution of a nucleophile for a leaving group in a carboxylic acid derivative. Identify the leaving group (Cl<sup>–</sup> in the case of an acid chloride) and the nucleophile (an alcohol in this case), and replace one by the other. The product is isopropyl benzoate.</para>
    <para id="para-00013"><title><span class="cyan-text">Solution</span></title></para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00008">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction of Benzoyl chloride in the presence of 2-propanol (highlighted in blue) to yield Isopropyl benzoate. Benzoyl chloride shows benzene bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to chlorine. The oxygen atoms are pink and the chlorine (a leaving group) is green. 2-propanol shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group bonded to a methyl group. The methine group is bonded to a hydroxyl group at the top. The hydroxyl oxygen shows four electrons (nucleophile). Isopropyl benzoate shows benzene bonded to a carbonyl group bonded to a blue oxygen bonded to a blue carbon bonded to two blue methyl groups and a blue hydrogen. The carbonyl oxygen is highlighted in pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_02_009.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </example>
